abstract: Even WILLIAM SHAKESPEARE made mistakes. His sombre comedy called "Measure for Measure," for instance, keeps that fact alive. In excellence of workmanship and in the charm and eloquence of its language it is beyond the reach of any other dramatic poet. Its characters are as true to human nature as it was the poet's wont to make them in all his plays, and its exalted aim is not to be questioned.

abstract: An Alaskan midsummer day is a day without night. In the extreme northern portion of the territory the sun does not set for weeks, and even as far south as Sitka and Fort Wrangel it sinks only a few degrees below the horizon, so that the rosy colors of the evening blend with those of the morning, leaving no gap of darkness between. Nevertheless, the full day opens slowly.

abstract: BOMBAY, Aug. 2. -- Fort Chakdara, in the Chitral district, which was besieged by a large force of insurgent natives, has been relieved by the British force under Gen. Blood. abstract: There is evidently need in this country of much more extensive instruction in the rudiments of civilization. abstract: ATLANTA, Ga., Aug. 21. -- The wholesale dealers, jobbers, and manufacturers of this city met to-day and perfected an organization modeled on the plan of the Merchants' Association of New York. abstract: The French Government in 1820 levied taxes of 939,000,000f.; in 1840 this sum had risen to 1,235,000,000f.; in 1869, to 1,962,000,000f.; in 1880, to 3,130,000,000f., and in 1895 the sum reached 3,375,000,000f. It has been calculated how much Government in France has cost per hour at various periods in this century. Under Napoleon I. the hourly expenditure was 150,000f.; under Louis XVIII., 119,000f.; under Louis Philippe, 150,000f.; under Napoleon III., 249,000f., and in 1882, 463,000f.

abstract: PARIS, Aug. 9. -- It is a strange, and at the same time a deplorable, fact, that European literature should be so poor in authoritative works on contemporary history. abstract: No straws point more accurately the course of general business affairs than the statistics of the Post Office and the telegraph companies. Languishing or dormant commercial conditions result in diminishing correspondence and fewer telegrams. On the other hand, in times of business activity, when the employment of capital assures handsome returns, correspondence is compulsory, while economy of time, necessitated by acute and stirring business situations, encourages lavish use of telegraph facilities.

abstract: CHICAGO, Aug. 28. -- The problem of communication by telegraph with a moving train anywhere on the line has been solved by George W. Trott, a young Chicago inventor. Mr. Trott has devised a system, which will shortly be given a trial on the Pennsylvania Railroad, by which every train on the line is in constant communication with the station next ahead, and, when desired, with the train dispatcher or any public telegraph station.

abstract: SEATTLE, Washington, Aug. 29. -- The steamer Portland arrived here at 3 o'clock this morning. It was fourteen hours after the Portland was sighted off Cape Flattery before she arrived here. The Portland carried thirteen miners, each of whom brought only a small part of his stake. Although reports that the Portland had brought a great treasure have been made, the actual value of the gold dust on board is perhaps $575,000.
